UMAP of Clusters:
UMAP of 156,572 cells yielded 40 transcriptionally distinct clusters at a resolution of 0.8, visualized in two-dimensional space using the first 15 principal components. The UMAP revealed several well-defined groups of clusters reflecting the major cell lineages of the nasal mucosa. A large dominant region on the left of the UMAP comprising clusters 0, 1, 6, 18 and 23 corresponds to the abundant neuronal population consistent with the olfactory sensory neurons known to comprise a large proportion of nasal mucosa tissue. Distinct clusters of epithelial, immune, and stromal cells were identified in the central and right regions of the UMAP. Several small isolated clusters including cluster 34 likely represent rare cell populations. The 40 clusters identified are broadly consistent with the 42 clusters reported in the source paper, with minor differences attributable to differences in clustering resolution and quality control parameters.

UMAP of Cell types:
UMAP colored by sample timepoint revealed thorough mixing of cells from all five timepoints (Naive, D02, D05, D08, D14) throughout every region of the UMAP space, confirming that clustering was driven by transcriptional cell type identity rather than sample-specific technical variation. The absence of timepoint-specific clustering indicated no significant batch effects between samples, consistent with the source paper's finding of reproducible sample replicates. Minor enrichment of D14 cells in specific smaller clusters was observed, likely reflecting the biologically documented accumulation of KNIIFE epithelial cells and tissue-resident memory T cells at this timepoint following viral clearance. These findings supported proceeding with downstream analysis without data integration.
